><p>100</p></td><td><p>107</p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p>1999</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>111</p></td><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>110</p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Data are in current prices, allowing cross-country comparison of productivity for each individual year.</p><p>Source: International Comparisons of Productivity, First Estimates for 2014, ONS (Sep 2015)</p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/icp/international-comparisons-of-productivity/2014---first-estimates/stb-icp0915.html" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/icp/international-comparisons-of-productivity/2014---first-estimates/stb-icp0915.html</a></p><p>* Productivity data for the G7 are unavailable for 1990 due to the absence of comparable data for pre-reunification Germany.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-12-10T12:24:35.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432581/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432581/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Productivity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what were the productivity levels in the UK compared with the rest of the G7 in each year since 1990.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432582","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-10","<p>The National Infrastructure Pipeline outlines over £410 billion of planned investment to the end of the decade and beyond; this includes both public and private investment.</p><br /><p>At the Spending Review, it was announced that the Government will exceed its commitment to invest £100 billion in infrastructure by 2020-21. It will now make a public investment of £120 billion. (This includes social infrastructure).</p><br /><p>HM Government does not hold figures on infrastructure spending in other G7 countries, and methodological discrepancies prevent reliable comparison of infrastructure spending.</p><br />",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-12-10T16:59:35.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432582/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432582/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Infrastructure: Capital Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the current level of spending on infrastructure in the UK, compared to the rest of the G7.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432583","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Chancellor announced at the Autumn Statement that the doubling of Small Business Rate Relief will continue for a further year and therefore apply for the whole of 2016-17. Approximately 600,000 properties are benefitting, with 400,000 paying no business rates at all.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-08T15:04:29.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432583/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432583/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Small Businesses: Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect on high streets of ending small business rate relief.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432584","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-10","<p>There is no single definition of food insecurity. The factors that impact on household food security are complex. There are multiple indicators such as quality, variety and desirability of diet as well as total intake, not all of which are measured consistently. It is therefore very difficult and potentially misleading to attempt to develop a single classification of food insecurity.</p><br /><p>Defra publishes statistics annually to show the proportion of household income spent on food by (a) all households and (b) the lowest income 20% of households.The most recent statistics are in the Food Statistics Pocketbook 2015 on the GOV.UK website.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-12-10T15:12:14.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432584/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432584/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-26","Food Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they have made no assessment of the number of people experiencing food insecurity.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432585","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) provides double rewards for biofuels derived from wastes.</p><br /><p>The Department concluded a post-implementation review of the RTFO in April 2014. Evidence from the review indicates that double rewards for biofuels from wastes, which were introduced under the RTFO in 2011, have encouraged a strong market for biodiesel from used cooking oil in the UK.</p><br /><p>Since the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) was established waste based biofuels have risen from 12% of total biofuel supply in the first year of the obligation 2008/09, to 50% according to the data for 2014/15 (<em>Biofuels Statistics obligation year 7 2014/15 - Report 5</em>).</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL3995","2015-12-04T12:07:39.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432585/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432585/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-26","Biofuels","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the viability of biodiesel made from waste products in comparison to biodiesel made from virgin products.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432586","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) provides double rewards for biofuels derived from wastes.</p><br /><p>The Department concluded a post-implementation review of the RTFO in April 2014. Evidence from the review indicates that double rewards for biofuels from wastes, which were introduced under the RTFO in 2011, have encouraged a strong market for biodiesel from used cooking oil in the UK.</p><br /><p>Since the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) was established waste based biofuels have risen from 12% of total biofuel supply in the first year of the obligation 2008/09, to 50% according to the data for 2014/15 (<em>Biofuels Statistics obligation year 7 2014/15 - Report 5</em>).</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL3994","2015-12-04T12:07:39.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432586/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432586/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-26","Biofuels","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support they are giving to producers of biodiesel made from waste products.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432587","Department for Education","false","2015-12-09","<p>We are protecting the core schools budget in real terms, enabling a per pupil protection for the dedicated schools grant (DSG) and the pupil premium. The DSG protection includes funding for special needs provision and funding for the education of children and young people in child and adolescent mental health services units.</p><br /><p>The Education Services Grant is not intended to fund special needs provision, psychological services, or child and adolescent mental health provision. The £600 million reduction to the Education Services Grant, announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, should therefore have no direct impact on the provision of these support services.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-09T14:12:16.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432587/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432587/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-26","Education: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on support services provided through the Education Services Grant to local authorities of the £600 million funding reduction announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 for (1) special needs provision, (2) psychological services, and (3) child and adolescent mental health provision.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL3996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432588","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-08","<p>DWP is aware of issues raised by Tower Hamlets Council. The Department’s housing costs team have contacted Tower Hamlets to ask for examples so the Department can look into their concerns.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-12-08T12:28:12.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432588/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432588/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Housing Benefit: Tower Hamlets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, following their failure to notify Tower Hamlets Council that Housing Benefit claimants had been migrated to Universal Credit, how many claimants have been overpaid Housing Benefit by that Council, and what action has been taken to ensure any overpayment recovery action is financially sustainable for those claimants.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL3997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432589","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. These are available on the Parliament website.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-12-08T12:27:43.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432589/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432589/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Social Security Benefits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have undertaken research to establish the number of households likely to be affected by the Benefit Cap in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL3998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432590","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-08","<p>A copy of the report by Savills into the opportunities for estate regeneration in Central London will be made available in the Library of the House once published.</p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-08T15:16:07.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432590/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432590/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Regeneration: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will place in the Library of the House a copy of the research by Savills into the opportunities for estate regeneration in London, commissioned by the Number 10 Policy Unit.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL3999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432591","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-08","<p>The research into the opportunities for estate regeneration across London was a result of general discussions with Savills and the Number 10 Policy Unit, which led to an approach by Savills to complete this work. The Number 10 Policy Unit commissioned this work as a single tender.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-08T15:14:48.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432591/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432591/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Regeneration: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the research by Savills into the opportunities for estate regeneration, commissioned by the Number 10 Policy Unit, was contracted through an open tendering process.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL4000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432592","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-08","<p>Shortlisted schemes are currently undergoing due diligence. Subject to this, we expect contracts to be signed in this financial year and the full £150 million to be committed. The final amount for each scheme is yet to be confirmed.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-08T15:12:50.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432592/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432592/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Housing Estates: Regeneration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much of the £150 million funding made available for the regeneration of local authority housing estates has been made available to each of the successful schemes.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL4001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432593","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Social Housing Regulator has a clear regulatory framework which it used in this case. As is normal practice the Social Housing Regulator is working closely with Circle as it continues to recover its repair service and improves its governance. The Regulator currently has sufficient assurance of Circle’s intention to address the issues and its progress in doing so, such that the Regulator considers it does not need to apply enforcement powers at this point. The Regulator will of course continue to examine new information that comes to light.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-08T15:31:24.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432593/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432593/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Circle Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they have taken in response to the Homes and Communities Agency's decision to downgrade Circle Housing Group's governance rating from G1 to G3 following its failure to manage properly its Repair and Maintenance Contract with the Kier Group.","false","Biography information for Baroness King of Bow",,"Baroness King of Bow","HL4002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432594","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-09","<p>Total departmental expenditure limits (TDEL) for the Department for International Development (DFID) are set on the basis of forecast Gross National Income (GNI) growth to enable the Government to meet the commitment to spend 0.7 per cent of GNI on official development assistance (ODA). Budgets also take into account assumptions for non-budgetary spend on ODA such as the UK’s share of EU ODA expenditure. As a result, DFID’s total DEL budget will increase by 8.5 per cent between 17/18 and 19/20.</p><br /><p>The split between capital and resource DEL is set to help manage pressures such as capital contributions to multilateral development banks.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-12-09T16:55:29.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432594/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432594/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Department for International Development: Departmental Expenditure Limits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they have increased the Resource Departmental Expenditure Limit for International Development by 16.1 per cent between 2017–18 and 2018–19, as per Table 1A of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Marlesford",,"Lord Marlesford","HL4003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432595","Department of Health","false","2015-12-03","<p>All NHS England commissioned secondary and tertiary hospitals will be able to collect blood and/or tissue samples for the purpose of genetic testing, depending on the sampling technique required. The testing itself is however usually undertaken by commissioned genetic laboratories, which will typically serve a catchment area much greater than the hospital in which they are based. There will usually be recommended criteria in place to guide National Health Service referrals for genetic testing.</p><br /><p>In a small number of cases, usually for very rare conditions, a test may need to be sent away to a non commissioned laboratory, including some abroad and some falling within the private sector, to access expertise. Funding will, however, continue to be provided from NHS budgets.</p><br /><p>The United Kingdom is also leading the world by using cutting edge technology in the form of whole genome sequencing to transform healthcare and health research. The Prime Minister launched the 100,000 Genomes Project to bring the benefits of genome sequencing to NHS patients. The Project will sequence 100,000 whole human genomes of NHS patients with cancer or a rare disease by the end of 2017. Eleven Genomic Medicine Centres have been established across the country and are recruiting patients to this landmark project. Otherwise, NHS England does not hold data on private or self-funded care or testing commissioned from either NHS or third party laboratories.</p><br /><p>Information on the percentage of eligible patients who received access to genetic testing is not held by NHS England. Due to data protection requirements, detailed data on the reasons for referral for specific tests are not currently aggregated at national level.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4005 ; HL4006 ; HL4007 ; HL4008","2015-12-03T14:27:14.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432595/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432595/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-26","Cancer","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of NHS tertiary care centres provide in-house tumour genetic testing in (1) breast cancer, (2) colorectal cancer, (3) lung cancer, and (4) melanoma.","false","Biography information for Lord Freyberg",,"Lord Freyberg","HL4004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432596","Department of Health","false","2015-12-03","<p>All NHS England commissioned secondary and tertiary hospitals will be able to collect blood and/or tissue samples for the purpose of genetic testing, depending on the sampling technique required. The testing itself is however usually undertaken by commissioned genetic laboratories, which will typically serve a catchment area much greater than the hospital in which they are based. There will usually be recommended criteria in place to guide National Health Service referrals for genetic testing.</p><br /><p>In a small number of cases, usually for very rare conditions, a test may need to be sent away to a non commissioned laboratory, including some abroad and some falling within the private sector, to access expertise. Funding will, however, continue to be provided from NHS budgets.</p><br /><p>The United Kingdom is also leading the world by using cutting edge technology in the form of whole genome sequencing to transform healthcare and health research. The Prime Minister launched the 100,000 Genomes Project to bring the benefits of genome sequencing to NHS patients. The Project will sequence 100,000 whole human genomes of NHS patients with cancer or a rare disease by the end of 2017. Eleven Genomic Medicine Centres have been established across the country and are recruiting patients to this landmark project. Otherwise, NHS England does not hold data on private or self-funded care or testing commissioned from either NHS or third party laboratories.</p><br /><p>Information on the percentage of eligible patients who received access to genetic testing is not held by NHS England. Due to data protection requirements, detailed data on the reasons for referral for specific tests are not currently aggregated at national level.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4004 ; HL4006 ; HL4007 ; HL4008","2015-12-03T14:27:14.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432596/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432596/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-26","Cancer","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of NHS secondary care centres provide in-house tumour genetic testing in (1) breast cancer, (2) colorectal cancer, (3) lung cancer, and (4) melanoma.","false","Biography information for Lord Freyberg",,"Lord Freyberg","HL4005"
