"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432600","Attorney General","false","2015-12-03","<p>Spending Review 2015 set out settlements for departments and showed how the government will deliver on its priorities, eliminate the deficit, and deliver security and opportunity for working people.</p><p>Final decisions on internal departmental funding allocations for future years, including for research and development, have not yet been made.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-12-03T11:11:25.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432600/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432600/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-11-26","Attorney General: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much of the Law Officers' Departments funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432601","Attorney General","false","2015-12-03","<p>The Government Legal Department provides training to all lawyers within the Government Legal Service, Attorney General’s Office and HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate, and hosted a training session on the legal implications of The Family Test in May 2015. While training places were prioritised for lawyers advising the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP), all government lawyers were eligible to apply.</p><p>In addition, the training committee within the DWP legal advisers will consider the inclusion of further training on The Family Test in response to any further needs identified.</p><p>The Serious Fraud Office and Crown Prosecution Service are not directly involved in frontline policy development and whilst they are aware of the published DWP guidance on applying the test, no specific training has been deemed necessary at this stage. However, they would of course apply the test should the need arise.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-12-03T11:06:43.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432601/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432601/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-11-26","Attorney General: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what training the Law Officers' Departments have provided to staff on the family test; what other steps he has taken to raise awareness of the family test among staff of the Law Officers' Departments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","17921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432602","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-03","<p>In Official Statistics types of business are subdivided by internationally agreed Standard Industrial Classification codes. These do not have sufficient detail to separately identify the hair industry but group this under SIC 96.02 - Hairdressing and other beauty treatment, which also includes facial, nail care and other make-up and beauty services. According to the latest Annual Business Survey (ONS) this industry accounted for 139,000 jobs in 2014.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-03T14:29:03.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432602/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432602/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Personal Care Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people are employed as practitioners within the UK hair industry.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John Mc Nally","17861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432603","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-03","<p>In Official Statistics types of business are subdivided by internationally agreed Standard Industrial Classification codes. These do not have sufficient detail to separately identify the hair industry but group this under SIC 96.02 - Hairdressing and other beauty treatment, which also includes facial, nail care and other make-up and beauty services. According to the latest ONS Annual Business Survey this industry contributed nearly £2.7bn in gross value added to the UK economy in 2014.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-03T12:52:28.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432603/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432603/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Personal Care Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the value of the hair industry to the economy.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John Mc Nally","17862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432604","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Chief Scientific Advisers work across departments in partnership with policy makers to ensure the very best in scientific evidence is used in the policy process. Where posts are unfilled, the Government Office for Science works with departments to ensure they have access to relevant expertise and evidence.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T15:18:47.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432604/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432604/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Government Departments: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his policy is on ensuring that all government departments have access to a chief scientific advisor.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","17872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432605","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Family Test was announced by my Rt. hon Friend the Prime Minister in August 2014 and introduced in October 2014.</p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills welcomed the introduction of the Family Test and has taken steps to embed it by building it into the Department’s Public Sector Equality Duty commitments. This has included training officials on applying the test, disseminating learning materials and best practice.</p><p>The Family Test is an integral part of the policy making process and is applied in a proportionate way in the development of all new policy in line with the Family Test guidance, published by the Department for Work and Pensions.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-20T08:31:06.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432605/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432605/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what training his Department has provided to staff on the family test; what other steps he has taken to raise awareness of the family test among staff of his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","17920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432606","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-02","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State, Ministers and officials in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and HM Treasury meet regularly to discuss policy.</p><p>The Government announced its proposals for a Master’s Loan at Autumn Statement and Spending Review 2015. Further information is available via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/postgraduate-study-student-loans-and-other-support" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/postgraduate-study-student-loans-and-other-support</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-02T15:39:50.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432606/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432606/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Postgraduate Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on his proposal in the Autumn Statement of 2014 to offer a student loan provision for postgraduate masters degrees.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","18006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432607","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) collects and publishes statistics on students enrolled at UK Higher Education Institutions (HEI). The most recent data covers the 2013-14 academic year. The latest figures for the numbers of higher education students who were living in the Burnley constituency, Lancashire, and the North West prior to study are presented in the following table:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Higher Education Enrolments by Region<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>UK Higher Education Institutions</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Academic Year 2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Undergraduate</p></td><td><p>Postgraduate</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Burnley</p></td><td><p>1,880</p></td><td><p>275</p></td><td><p>2,155</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lancashire</p></td><td><p>28,050</p></td><td><p>5,760</p></td><td><p>33,810</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>162,080</p></td><td><p>34,040</p></td><td><p>196,125</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Source: Higher Education Statistics Agency</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Note: Figures rounded to the nearest multiple of 5</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p><sup>1</sup>Parliamentary constituency is derived from student's postcode</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T15:12:39.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432607/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432607/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Higher Education: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people from (a) Burnley, (b) Lancashire and (b) the North West are currently in higher education.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","18005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432608","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-01","<p>The information is not held centrally.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-01T10:11:21.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432608/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432608/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Universities: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of universities make unconditional offers to 18 year olds applying to study at those universities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","17978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432609","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-03","<p>Table 1 shows the number of Apprenticeships started in the ‘Engineering and Manufacturing Technologies’, ‘Information and Communication Technology’ and ‘Science and Mathematics’ Sector Subject Areas since May 2010.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Table 1: Number of Apprenticeship starts in the Engineering and Manufacturing Technologies, Information and Communication Technology and Science and Mathematics Sector Subject Areas since May 2010 (May 2010 to July 2015)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Sector Subject Area</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Starts since May 2010</strong></p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p>Engineering and Manufacturing Technologies</p></td><td><p>337,400</p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p>Information and Communication Technology</p></td><td><p>82,760</p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p>Science and Mathematics</p></td><td><p>1,440</p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 421,600 </strong></p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>1) The source is the Individualised Learner Record.</p></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>2) Volumes are rounded to the nearest 10, with the exception of totals which are rounded to the nearest hundred.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-03T12:11:07.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432609/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432609/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Apprentices: STEM Subjects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many apprenticeships have been taken up in STEM industries since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","17937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432610","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>The UK welcomes international students and there is no cap on the number that can study here. The Government promotes study in the UK through the Britain is GREAT marketing campaign and through the British Council, which promotes UK education in over 100 countries, connecting millions of people with the United Kingdom.</p><p>The Government has a number of major education agreements with overseas partners. Key programmes include the UK-China Partners in Education Programme, the UK-India Education Research Initiative and engagement in Brazil’s ‘Science without Borders’ scholarship scheme.</p><p>Government also supports student exchange, such as through the Erasmus Scheme, which enables international students to take short placements in the UK and British students to gain valuable overseas experience.</p><p>As part of our recent Spending Review the Government has also reaffirmed the importance international students to the success of UK universities and the economy. To ensure universities can continue to compete with the US, Australia and Canada for top international students, dependants of postgraduates on courses lasting more than a year will be welcome to come and work. Current English language requirements will be maintained.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T15:12:08.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432610/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432610/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK remains competitive with other countries in attracting overseas students to higher and further education; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","17938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432611","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-01","<br /><p>It is our intention that the Institute for Apprenticeships will be fully operational by April 2017 and we expect it to begin operating in shadow form during 2016, taking on functions in a phased transition.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-01T16:06:21.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432611/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432611/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Apprentices: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans for the new business-led body to set standards for apprenticeships as announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 to come into operation.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","18024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432612","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-02","<p>At the Autumn Statement, my Rt hon Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced the Government will establish a new employer-led body to set apprenticeship standards and ensure quality. The body will be independent of Government and will also advise on the level of levy funding each apprenticeship should receive. Our expectation is that funding caps will be significantly higher for programmes which have high costs and are of high quality.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-02T09:50:55.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432612/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432612/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, by how much the Government plans to increase the funding per place for apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","18025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432613","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Spending Review announced that we will protect the Science Budget in real terms throughout this Parliament, with resource funding of £4.7 billion per year, while delivering on our manifesto commitment to invest in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale: £6.9 billion up to 2021.</p><p>The Comprehensive Spending Review set out the high level budgets for my department. The total planned expenditure on research and development through to 2020 will be confirmed in due course following an internal allocations process.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T15:18:08.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432613/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432613/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432614","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-03","<p>Late payment remains an important issue for small businesses in the UK. The Government is taking significant steps to assist small businesses to recover late payment debts.</p><p>Through the Enterprise Bill, currently before Parliament, we will legislate to establish a Small Business Commissioner to help small business resolve disputes with large companies, tackling, in particular, late payment. The Commissioner will act as a disincentive to unfavourable payment practices, and build the confidence and capabilities of small businesses to help them to assert themselves in contractual disputes and negotiate more effectively with larger businesses.</p><p>This is part of a package of measures to tackle late payment. We have also legislated for new transparency measures in the public and private sectors. This will allow full public scrutiny of payment performance.</p><p>We have also strengthened the Prompt Payment Code to ensure it is a recognised and demonstrated beacon of best practice, and we recently consulted on proposals to give representative bodies wider powers to challenge grossly unfair payment practices.</p><p>Tackling late payment is about creating a responsible payment culture where larger companies recognise the benefit of having a sustainable and robust supply chain, and smaller businesses feel able to challenge poor behaviour. Once implemented, the Government is confident that these measures will lead to significant changes in the UK’s payment culture.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-03T12:51:43.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432614/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432614/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Small Businesses: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the Government is doing to assist small businesses to recover debts.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","17794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432615","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-03","<p>The rules governing the power to enter a commercial property for enforcement by taking control of goods are contained in Schedule 12 to the Tribunals, Courts and Enforcement Act 2007. Enforcement under a High Court Writ, which was the responsibility of Sheriffs, is now carried out by High Court Enforcement Officers pursuant to the High Court Enforcement Officers Regulations 2004. Paragraphs 14 to 30 of Schedule 12 (as amended by the Crime and Courts Act 2013) make provision concerning powers of entry for the purposes of enforcement, and paragraphs 18A and 19 make provision specifically in relation to the power to use reasonable force to enter premises at which the enforcement officer reasonably believes the debtor carries on a trade or a business. The Ministry of Justice has produced guidance, the Taking Control of Goods: National Standards, to support creditors and enforcement agents and promote minimum standards. It is available on the Gov.uk website.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-12-03T13:44:40.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432615/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432615/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-26","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what (a) regulations and (b) guidance apply to Sheriffs breaking into commercial properties to recover debts.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","17795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432616","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-01","<br /> <br /><p>I refer the Hon Member to my reply to the hon Member for Newport West to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-10-09/11271/" target="_blank">11271</a>.</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-01T15:23:29.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432616/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432616/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what consultation his Department carried out with (a) students and their representative bodies and (b) other people and bodies before announcing that university maintenance grants would be abolished.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","17803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432617","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-01","<p>New students starting full-time courses from 1 August 2016 onwards who would otherwise have received a grant will qualify for an increased loan for living costs. The total living costs support available in 2016/17 under the new student support arrangements for eligible students on the lowest incomes is increasing by 10.3% when compared with 2015/16.</p><br /><p>The Government expects to lay amendments to the Student Support Regulations covering student support for 2016/17 shortly.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-01T10:12:36.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432617/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432617/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on what timetable he plans to abolish university maintenance grants, including the timetable for laying associated regulations.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","17804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432618","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Government expects to publish an Equality Analysis of the changes to student support for the 2016/17 academic year alongside the regulations.</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-01T15:21:42.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432618/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432618/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-26","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of replacing maintenance grants with loans on students from faith backgrounds which discourage the accrual of interest.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","17805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432619","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster is responsible to the Sovereign for the administration of the estates of the Duchy of Lancaster, in which he is assisted by the Duchy Council. The Chancellor also appoints various Duchy representatives on university councils, school governing bodies and charities in the County Palatine.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-12-01T14:52:34.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432619/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432619/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what responsibilities the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster has which relate to the Duchy of Lancaster.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","17798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432620","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-07","<p>It is a tribute to the dedication and work of individual Civil Servants that job satisfaction remains high and wellbeing has increased. It should be a source of pride that the Civil Service has successfully changed the way it operates and become more efficient - it is now delivering far more, for less, than it did before 2010.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-07T09:01:55.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432620/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432620/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432620/answer/previousversion/33016","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Civil Servants: Job Satisfaction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the Minister's assessment is of morale in the civil service.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432621","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-01","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave her on 26 November 2015 to UIN: 10865-10866 and on 30 November 2015 to UIN: 17505.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-01T14:53:04.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432621/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432621/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Cabinet Office: Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many positions are being created within his Extended Ministerial Office in each pay grade.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432622","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Following settlement of the Cabinet Office Spending Review last week, the allocation of funds to individual workstreams, including for research and development, is underway as part of the department’s business planning process to be completed in the coming months.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","17773","2015-12-02T14:39:34.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432622/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432622/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Cabinet Office: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432623","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-04","<p>The Spending Review settlement has shown Government's continued commitment to digital delivery of services to recast the relationship between the citizen and the state. £1.8 billion investment in digital technology was announced by the Government in the Spending Review, plus a £450m allocation for GDS.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-04T16:37:22.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432623/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432623/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432623/answer/previousversion/33019","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Government Digital Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Departmental Settlement within the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what proportion of his Department's resource DEL is allocated to the Government Digital Service and related projects in each year to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432624","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>Following settlement of the Cabinet Office Spending Review last week, the allocation of funds to individual management units is underway as part of the department’s business planning process to be completed in the coming months.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-02T14:40:12.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432624/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432624/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432624/answer/previousversion/33020","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Cabinet Office: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the planned operational budget is for the (a) Government Innovation Group and (b) Efficiency and Reform Group announced in the Departmental Settlement within the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 in each year to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432625","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-03","<p>At Summer Budget the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced that families will no longer be able to claim additional support through Child Tax Credit or Universal Credit for third or subsequent children in a family where the child is born after April 2017. In addition families making a completely new claim to Universal Credit after April 2017 will no longer be entitled to support for their third or subsequent children.</p><br /><p>A family currently claiming Child Tax Credit with three or more children will see no change to their household income because of this change. This policy will only affect families claiming Child Tax Credit where they have a third or subsequent child on or after 6 April 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-03T16:32:19.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432625/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432625/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the effect on the household income of a family in receipt of tax credits with (a) three, (b) four and (c) five children of the Government's proposals to limit claims for tax credit and universal credit to two children as announced in the Summer Budget 2015 and the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","17935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-08","<p>At the summer budget the Chancellor of the Exchequer set out the Government’s commitment to move the UK from a high tax, high welfare, low wage society to a lower tax, lower welfare, higher wage society. This remains the case, and Universal Credit (UC) is delivering this.</p><p>UC is a fundamentally different benefit to the legacy benefit system and provides people with support into, and to progress in work.</p><p>Therefore there is no meaningful way of comparing an unreformed Tax Credit system with Universal Credit. The Government has committed to transitional arrangements as we reform the benefits and Tax Credit system. Those transferred by DWP from tax credits to UC will receive Transitional Protection. In addition, estimates of entitlements under UC of the sort requested will vary depending on assumptions on the level of earnings.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","17934 ; 18169 ; 18170 ; 18171 ; 18172 ; 18173 ; 18174 ; 18175 ; 18226","2015-12-08T17:37:09.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432626/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the effect on the household income of a family with two earners and three children which becomes a new claimant of universal credit and which is not migrating from a legacy benefit of the Government's proposed changes to universal credit announced in the Summer Budget 2015 in each of the next four financial years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","17936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432627","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-04","<p>Revenue protected in connection with avoidance measures announced over the last 6 years is scored in relevant Budget documentation published by HM Treasury.</p><br /><p>However, for convenience on 19 March 2015 the coalition government published a document detailing the action taken over the course of the last Parliament to tackle tax evasion and avoidance. That document can be found at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tackling-tax-evasion-and-avoidance" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/tackling-tax-evasion-and-avoidance</a></p><p><br></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-04T13:07:09.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432627/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432627/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the benefit to the public purse was of the closing of tax loopholes in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","17973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432628","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-03","<p>This issue is a matter for the Department for Work and Pensions. I understand that the Minister for Work and Pensions has responded to an identical question tabled by the hon Member.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-03T17:04:54.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432628/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432628/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the effect on the household income of a family with one earner and two children which becomes a new claimant of universal credit and is not migrating from a legacy benefit of the Government's proposed changes to universal credit announced in the Summer Budget 2015 in each of the next four financial years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","17940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432629","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-01","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost</p><p><em></em></p><p><em></em></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","17882 ; 17883 ; 18029","2015-12-01T14:50:54.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432629/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432629/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the effect on the income of a new claimant of universal credit who is not migrating from a legacy benefit of the Government's proposed changes to universal credit announced in the Summer Budget 2015 in each of the next four financial years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","17941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432630","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of companies and organisations to discuss relevant issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-02T17:41:47.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432630/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432630/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many times he has met (a) insurance companies and (b) personal injury law firms in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","18028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432631","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-01","<p>This policy was introduced because in some areas, increases in social rents have outstripped the increase in private rents.</p><br /><p>The policy to cap social sector rents at the relevant Local Housing Allowance rate for the area from April 2018 only applies to a new tenancy or a tenancy that is renewed after April 2016. As such it isn’t possible to accurately estimate the proportion of those in receipt of Housing Benefit in the social sector that will be affected by this policy, as it relies on the choice of those taking out new tenancies.</p><br /><p>The Discretionary Housing Payment scheme will be available to Local Authorities to protect the vulnerable.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-01T15:19:33.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432631/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432631/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Housing Benefit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of people in the social housing sector in Scotland will be affected by changes to the levels of housing benefit; and what the cost of such changes will be to the average household in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","18018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432632","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-08","<p>At the summer budget the Chancellor of the Exchequer set out the Government’s commitment to move the UK from a high tax, high welfare, low wage society to a lower tax, lower welfare, higher wage society. This remains the case, and Universal Credit (UC) is delivering this.</p><p>UC is a fundamentally different benefit to the legacy benefit system and provides people with support into, and to progress in work.</p><p>Therefore there is no meaningful way of comparing an unreformed Tax Credit system with Universal Credit. The Government has committed to transitional arrangements as we reform the benefits and Tax Credit system. Those transferred by DWP from tax credits to UC will receive Transitional Protection. In addition, estimates of entitlements under UC of the sort requested will vary depending on assumptions on the level of earnings.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","17936 ; 18169 ; 18170 ; 18171 ; 18172 ; 18173 ; 18174 ; 18175 ; 18226","2015-12-08T17:37:08.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432632/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432632/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Welfare Tax Credits: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the average transitional protection award that will be paid to the claimants who are migrated from tax credits to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","17934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432633","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of companies and organisations to discuss relevant issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-02T17:16:20.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432633/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432633/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings he, his Ministers or officials have had since the 2015 General Election with (a) insurance companies, (b) claimant personal injury solicitors and (c) defendant personal injury solicitors; and who attended any such meeting.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","17980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432634","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Pensions Regulator has already taken steps to ensure that occupational pension schemes are aware of the findings of the Law Commission’s report on fiduciary duties.</p><br /><p>In October 2014 The Pensions Regulator emailed over 37,000 pension scheme trustees to make them aware of the Law Commission’s report, and the guidance produced by the Law Commission on pension trustees’ duties.</p><br /><p>The Pensions Regulator has also updated its ‘trustee toolkit’ training materials to reflect the Law Commission’s findings, and is updating its investment guidance with new material with reflects the Law Commission’s conclusions. This includes the revised Code of Practice and guidance for running defined contribution schemes, which is currently published for consultation.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-04T09:22:38.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432634/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432634/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-26","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to ensure that all UK Pension schemes are aware of (a) the findings of the Law Commission's report on Fiduciary Duties of Investment Intermediaries, published in June 2014, HC 368, and (b) related guidance to be issued by the Pensions Regulator.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432635","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>A list of the Open Banking Working Group (OBWG) participants was published on 23 November, setting out the organisations which are directly involved in designing the detailed framework for the open Application Programming Interface (API) standard in UK banking by the end of the year. The OBWG will publish its final report on 30 December. More detail is available on the Open Data Institute’s website.</p><br /><p>A number of consumer organisations have participated in the development of the framework for the open API standard: the Money Advice Service is a direct member of the OBWG, and Citizens Advice and Which? have participated in discussions about its design.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-02T17:11:36.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432635/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432635/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Open Banking Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what consumer organisations have been involved in the work of the Open Banking Working Group; and when that group is expected to report.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","17887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432636","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-04","<p>The estimated proportion of small- and medium-sized enterprise employers failing to fully meet their obligations in respect of operating Pay As You Earn (PAYE) is published in ‘Measuring Tax Gaps; 2015 edition' (table 6.8, p.53).</p><br /><p>Comparable figures for large employers are not available, but an estimate of the tax gap for large employers can be found on table 6.9, also on p.53.</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps</a></p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-04T13:03:52.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432636/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432636/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Personal Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what change there has been in the incidence of failure by employees to pay appropriate tax and National Insurance.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","17873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432637","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-04","<p>Estimates of the proportion of payments of (a) income tax and (b) National Insurance by employees (i) within and (ii) outside the UK that were correctly made are not available.</p><br /><p>Estimates of the value of under-declared income tax and national insurance liabilities resulting from incorrect returns are published in chapter 6 of ‘Measuring Tax Gaps 2015.’ These are produced for both small and medium enterprise (SME) employers (table 6.7) and large employers (table 6.9).</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-04T13:02:40.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432637/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432637/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of payments of (a) income tax and (b) National Insurance by employees (i) within and (ii) outside the UK were made correctly in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","17881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432638","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-01","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) first shared its transformation plans with its employees 18 months ago. Since then, it has held more than 2,000 events across the UK, talking to its employees about how and why it is changing. HMRC will be holding one-to-one discussions with each of its people to discuss next steps.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-01T16:45:14.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432638/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432638/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he made the decision to close 170 local tax offices and replace them with 13 regional centres.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","17814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432639","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>The following table outlines the number of full time equivalent staff employed at the tax credit office in Preston at the start of each financial year<strong>.</strong></p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Number of full time equivalent staff</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2010</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2011</p></td><td><p>1957</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2012</p></td><td><p>1998</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2013</p></td><td><p>2033</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014</p></td><td><p>1870</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015</p></td><td><p>1787</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>The projected full time equivalent staffing levels in 2016, 2017 and 2018 are 2,050, 1,941 and 1,834 respectively.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-02T17:43:01.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432639/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432639/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Revenue and Customs: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many full time equivalent staff were employed at the tax credit office in Preston in each year from 2010 to 2015; and what estimate he has made of the size of the workforce at that office in (a) 2016, (b) 2017 and (c) 2018.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","17816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432640","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>The UK Debt Management Office’s (DMO) key objectives are required to be met with due regard to the principles of ‘openness, transparency and predictability’, as set out in the annual Debt and Reserves Management Report. The DMO publishes and lays before Parliament its annual Business Plan and Annual Report and Accounts (and also publishes an Annual Review), providing information about its operations in line with these objectives. As an Executive Agency of the Treasury, the Chief Executive of the DMO is accountable to government and parliament, as set out in the DMO’s Executive Agency Framework Document.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-02T17:39:52.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432640/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432640/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","UK Debt Management Office","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to improve the transparency and accountability to (a) Government and (b) Parliament of the UK Debt Management Office.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","17792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432641","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-01","<p>The full list of successful Enterprise Zones, which is available to view online, was published by the Department of Communities and Local Government following the Spending Review announcement.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-01T16:34:42.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432641/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432641/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Enterprise Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.251 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what the 26 new Enterprise Zones are; and which local enterprise partnerships made unsuccessful applications to become enterprise zones.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","17793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432642","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>The information is not held in the form requested. However, information relating to total passengers and APD paid over the last five years are published in the Air Passenger Duty Tax and Duty bulletin at the following address: https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-02T16:20:12.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432642/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432642/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Aviation: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what amount of taxation was levied on air travel in each of the last five years per (a) passenger and (b) tonne of cargo carried.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","17787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432643","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Government is committed to Welsh language programming and to the future of S4C. This is why the Secretary of State announced on the 3 February that S4C’s funding would be protected in 2016/17 at current levels (£6.8m). In order for S4C to continue to provide a first-class service and have a sustainable future, the Government also intends to carry out a comprehensive review in 2017. This will look at the remit, governance and funding of S4C to ensure the broadcaster can continue to meet the needs of Welsh speaking audiences in the future. The additional funding announced on 3 February will ensure financial stability through the review process.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-24T17:00:07.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432643/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432643/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","S4C: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his plans are for future funding of S4C.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","17784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432644","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>Spending Review 2015 set out settlements for departments and showed how the government will deliver on its priorities, eliminate the deficit, and deliver security and opportunity for working people.</p><br /><p>Final decisions on internal departmental funding allocations for future years, including for research and development, have not yet been made.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-02T16:04:45.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432644/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432644/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Treasury: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432645","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-03","<p>The £15m estimate of the annual VAT revenue from sanitary products is produced by HM Revenue and Customs and is consistent with the published estimate of the cost of the current 5% relief for sanitary products (available to view here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a> ).</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-03T17:07:15.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432645/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432645/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Sanitary Products: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.114 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what the evidential basis for the estimate of £15 million annual tax receipt on sanitary products; and to what range of products that estimate applies.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","17820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432646","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Government’s spending priorities are not, in general, determined by the way in which the money is raised. All revenue received, in combination with the amount borrowed or repaid by the Government, contributes to the amount that the Government can spend in total. However, we will continue to look at each case on its merits.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-04T13:04:53.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432646/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432646/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on the hypothecation of revenues raised from VAT on specific products for a specific purpose.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","17992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432647","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-03","<p>Following the Chancellor’s Autumn Statement, it was announced on the London Stock Exchange at 2:57pm on 25 November 2015 that HMG is not providing £1bn capital grant funding.</p><br /><p>We have not taken this decision lightly. However, this was a tight financial settlement and difficult decisions have had to be made. Support for the CCS competition projects has always been conditional on affordability and value for money.</p><br /><p>This decision means that the CCS Competition cannot proceed on its current basis. CCS has a potential role in the long-term decarbonisation of the UK and the government is engaging closely with the bidders on the implications of this decision for them.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-03T16:58:52.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432647/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432647/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-26","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons the closure of the competition for carbon capture and storage projects was announced on a Stock Market news website on 25 November 2015, in advance of the Autumn Statement and Spending Review 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","17999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432648","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-02","<p>The 2015 Spending Review set out settlements for departments and showed how the Government will deliver on its priorities, eliminate the deficit, and deliver security and opportunity for working people.</p><p>Final decisions on internal departmental funding allocations for future years, including for research and development, have not yet been made.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-02T16:05:15.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432648/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432648/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Department for Communities and Local Government: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432649","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>Decisions around locally funded services will be set out in the provisional Local Government Settlement, which we intend to announce before recess.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-01T16:13:14.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432649/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432649/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has for the future of the homelessness prevention grant.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","17811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432650","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-02","<p>The Autumn Statement announced measures to double the number of first time buyers and confirmed £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable housing starts including £4 billion for 135,000 new Help to Buy: Shared Ownership starts by 2020. This will build on the 41,000 new Shared Ownership homes we have delivered since 2010.</p><p>We believe that shared ownership has an important role to play, as part of a diverse and thriving housing market, in helping those who aspire to home ownership but may be otherwise unable to afford it. The Government is also committed to working with housing associations to help to develop flexible tenure models and savings vehicles. This could include tenants converting their rented properties into shared ownership, overpaying on their rent in order to take an equity share in their property.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-02T16:03:59.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432650/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432650/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Shared Ownership Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to extend schemes of shared ownership for existing housing stock.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","17781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432651","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-02","<p>My Department does not hold this data, as decisions about the provision of bus services that require subsidy are a matter for individual English local authorities, in the light of their other spending priorities. Latest figures (2013-14) show that almost £74 million was spent by local authorities in the North West of England doing so.</p><br /><p>The majority of public funding for local bus services is via block grant provided to local authorities in England from the Department for Communities and Local Government. However, my Department also provides around £40m of Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) funding directly to English local authorities to help deliver bus services.</p><br /><p>Moreover, in the recent Spending Review, the Chancellor confirmed that the total spending on BSOG of around £250 million a year will be protected for the Parliament, effectively preserving over 80 million bus passenger journeys - totalling over 50 million miles - in England every year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-12-02T16:09:06.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432651/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432651/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-26","Bus Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which scheduled bus journeys have had subsidies (a) withdrawn and (b) introduced in each (i) county and (ii) unitary council in the North West of England since June 2010.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","17819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432652","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>Through the Spending Review the Government has committed to investing £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable housing starts doubling our investment in affordable housing from 2018-19.</p><p>This funding includes £1.7 billion for around 100,000 homes for affordable or intermediate rent, which will be delivered by 2021.</p><p>Since April 2010 we have delivered over 260,000 affordable homes. Under Labour the stock of affordable homes fell by 420,000, with 1.8 million families on social housing waiting lists. More council housing has been built since 2010 than in the previous 13 years of a Labour Government.</p><p>The Government does not publish annual delivery targets for the affordable housing programme.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-01T16:12:35.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432652/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432652/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Social Rented Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding the Government plans to make available (a) to housing associations, (b) to local authorities and (c) in total in each of the next four years to build social rented housing.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","17890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432653","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>Through the Spending Review the Government has committed to investing £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable housing starts, doubling our investment in affordable housing from 2018-19.</p><p>This includes £1.7 billion to deliver around 100,000 homes for affordable or intermediate rent. Already through the 2015-18 Affordable Homes programme we have allocated over £1 billion to deliver affordable housing, with the majority being for rented housing.</p><p>Since April 2010 we have delivered over 260,000 affordable homes. Under Labour the stock of affordable homes fell by 420,000, with 1.8 million families on social housing waiting lists. More council housing has been built since 2010 than in the previous 13 years of a Labour Government.</p><p>The funding allocated to housing associations and local authorities will depend on the bids submitted to the Affordable Homes programme.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-01T16:11:10.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432653/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432653/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Social Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of social rented homes that will be completed in (a) 2015-16 and (b) each of the succeeding four years.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","17891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432654","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>Through the Spending Review the Government has committed to investing £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable housing starts, doubling our investment from 2018-19.</p><p>This funding includes £1.7 billion for around 100,000 homes for affordable or intermediate rent, which will be delivered between 2015 and 2021.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-01T16:14:12.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432654/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432654/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many new social rented homes he plans will be funded by the resources identified for housing in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","17892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432655","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Spending Review and Autumn Statement made last week reaffirmed this Government’s commitment to keeping the country building, to delivering the homes communities want and supporting hard-working people who aspire to own their own home to be able to do so.</p><p>Over £20 billion was secured for housing from the Spending Review. This includes £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable starts, and a further £12 billion of housing investment which will support our 1 million homes ambition by 2020/21.</p><p>The Spending Review package announced last week supports a variety of tenures, including affordable homes for rent, shared ownership schemes and starter homes. It also supports home ownership through supporting custom build, the extension of Help to Buy, and extending the Right to Buy to tenants of housing associations.</p><p>Precise splits between differing types of tenure will depend on the nature and quality of bids recieved for new funding programmes, and on the type of sites coming forward.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-01T17:34:32.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432655/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432655/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many new homes of each type of tenure he plans will be funded by measures announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","17893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432656","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-03","<p>Cabinet Office records show that two buildings listed have been sold in central London on a long lease in the last 10 years.</p><br /><p>The first is Admiralty Arch, which is leased on a 250 year long lease,generating over £65 million in capital receipts for the exchequer.</p><br /><p>The second is the Old War Office, leased on a 250 year long lease. Both freeholds remain with Cabinet Office for the perpetuity.</p><br /><p>Information is only held centrally on the Government Estate in central London. Any information outside of this is held locally by departments.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-03T11:22:55.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432656/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432656/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432656/answer/previousversion/33024","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Government Departments: Listed Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which former Government-owned listed properties have been sold either as freehold or on a long lease in London in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","18017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432657","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not employ any civil servants, or secondees from outside bodies within the Property Asset Management Unit.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-01T16:15:15.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432657/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432657/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Government Property Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people are employed in the Property Asset Management Unit; and how many such people are (a) civil servants and (b) secondees from outside bodies.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","18015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432658","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>Records held by the Cabinet Office show that New Burlington House, Piccadilly is leased out via five separate leases for ten years, renewable, at a market rent to each of the five Learned Societies (Geological Society of London, Linnean Society of London, Royal Astronomical Society, Society of Antiquaries of London, Royal Society of Chemistry). Records also show that 157-197 Buckingham Palace Road is part sub-let by the National Audit Office to commercial sub-tenants.</p><p>Information is only held centrally on the Government Estate in London. Any information outside of this is held locally by departments.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-02T14:04:46.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432658/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432658/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432658/answer/previousversion/33023","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-26","Government Departments: Listed Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which listed properties owned in London by the Government are leased out; and to whom and on what terms such properties are leased.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","18016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432659","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Fire and Rescue Service provide a mass decontamination response capability on behalf of the Ambulance Service, which is deployable 24 hours a day, seven days a week, as part of the DCLG New Dimensions Programme.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2015-12-04T13:47:00.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432659/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432659/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Emergency Services: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many incident response units for the mass decontamination of members of the public there are in England which could be used in the event of a CBRNE attack; and how many such units are able to be deployed 24 hours a day, seven days a week.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","17983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432660","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-04","<p><br>Statistics on the numbers of first-time house buyers are published by the Council of Mortgage Lenders and can be found at:</p><p>https://www.cml.org.uk/home/</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-04T14:50:06.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432660/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432660/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","First Time Buyers: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many first-time house buyers there were in (a) Burnley, (b) Lancashire and (c) the North West in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","17972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432661","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-01","Each local authority is responsible for providing a comprehensive and efficient library service that meets the requirements of their communities, including consideration of opening hours.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-01T17:16:54.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432661/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432661/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Public Libraries: Opening Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the proportion of libraries which have reduced their opening hours in the last five years; and what assessment he has made of the effect of such changes on (a) library users and (b) community groups who use library premises.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","17888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432662","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-01","<p>TheSpending Review settlement puts national arts and culture organisations on a strong footing. It will ensure continued free access to national museums and galleries and allow them to pursue an ambitious agenda across this Parliament. As the Chancellor said in his Spending Review speech, &quot;one of the best investments we can make as a nation is in our extraordinary arts, museums, heritage, media and sport&quot;.</p><p><br>Forecast increases to other sources of income (including business rates and council tax) mean that local government spending is forecast to be higher in cash terms in 2019/20 than in 2015/16 . Local authorities understand the importance of investing in cultural activities in their areas, and are best placed to decide how to prioritise their spending.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-01T17:15:52.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432662/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432662/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Arts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of reduction to local government spending announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 on (a) local and (b) national arts and culture organisations.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","17886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432663","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Family Test was announced by the Prime Minister in August 2014 and introduced in October 2014. DWP published guidance for Departments and officials on how the test should be applied when formulating policy and my Department follows that guidance -<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368894/family-test-guidance.pdf" target="_blank">FamilyTestGuidance</a>.</p><p>Officials in my Department have liaised with DWP as the lead Department for the Family Test to embed it into the policy process. This could include training officials on applying the Test and disseminating relevant evidence, learning materials and best practice.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-17T10:23:26.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432663/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432663/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what training his Department has provided to staff on the family test; what other steps he has taken to raise awareness of the family test among staff of his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","17922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432664","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2015-12-01","<p><del class="ministerial">As recently reported, UK Sport's international relations grant to British Athletics contained an amount of £63,000 used to support the communications costs of Lord Coe's year-long election campaign. In addition, approximately £7,000 has also been spent on seconded UK Sport staff assisting with the campaign.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">As recently reported, UK Sport's international relations grant to British Athletics contained an amount of £63,000 used to support the communications costs of Lord Coe's year-long election campaign. In addition, approximately £7,000 has also been spent on seconded UK Sport staff and an independent contractor assisting with the campaign.</ins></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-01T17:10:17.257Z","2015-12-02T14:16:41.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432664/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432664/answer","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432664/answer/previousversion/33128","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Lord Coe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much UK Sport spent in support of the campaign of Lord Coe becoming President of the IAAF on (a) fees to consultancies, (b) direct payments to Lord Coe's campaign team, (c) travel and subsistence, (d) entertainment expenses and (e) other items.","false","Biography information for Damian Collins","Folkestone and Hythe","Damian Collins","17827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432665","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-03","<p>Ministers are considering a number of measures relating to local Heritage management as part of the Cultural White Paper, which will be published in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-03T16:31:21.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432665/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432665/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Listed Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on the introduction of application fees for listed building consent.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","17782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432666","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-04","<p>The Government is committed to extending home ownership opportunities for everyone. Disabled people with aspirations to own their own home can benefit from a number of policies offered by this Government, like Help to Buy and Right to Buy. However, we do recognise that for some people with long-term disabilities, our mainstream home ownership programmes may not be suitable. The Home Ownership for those with Long-term Disabilities (HOLD) scheme is specifically designed to help people living with such disabilities to buy a property on the open market on shared ownership terms with a registered housing provider.</p><p>The Government is also providing affordable housing for disabled and older people through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund, phase 1 of which will deliver around 4,000 new homes by 2018. Between 2011-15 the Affordable Homes Programme has also delivered almost 14,000 specialised and mainstream affordable homes for older and disabled people.</p><p>In the Spending Review we have committed to £400 million of funding to deliver 8,000 specialist homes for the vulnerable elderly or those with disabilities. A commitment to funding from the Department of Health could deliver up to a further 7,500 homes over the Spending Review period.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-04T13:42:55.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432666/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432666/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-26","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to help increase the number of disabled people who own their own home.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","17783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432667","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-08","Spending Review 2015 set out settlements for departments and showed how the government will deliver on its priorities, eliminate the deficit, and deliver security and opportunity for working people.<p><br>Final decisions on internal departmental funding allocations for future years, including for research and development, will be set out in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-08T14:28:22.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432667/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432667/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-26","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432668","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-03","<p>I refer the hon. Member to para 6.44 of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 (Cm9161) for the proportion of our defence budget dedicated to science and technology.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-03T16:38:33.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432668/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432668/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-26","Ministry of Defence: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much of his Department's funding allocated in the Spending Review 2015 will be for research and development expenditure up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","17761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432669","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-04","<br /><p>This information is not available in the format requested. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) routinely distinguishes between military and civilian travel and subsistence costs only where these are reimbursed to the individual under our pay and claim arrangements.</p><br /><p>Overall departmental expenditure on travel and subsistence has, however, been as follows:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Expenditure</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£226 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£213 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£213 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£212 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£221 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Expenditure by the Defence Ministers on travel and subsistence has been as follows.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Expenditure</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£297,126</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£295,922</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£225,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£262,184</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£259,849</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Note: This expenditure includes road transport, rail travel, international and domestic flights and the notional costs of travel in RAF aircraft where they have been available.</p><br /><p>Travel by the Defence Ministers and all departmental staff makes a key contribution to achieving Defence objectives. The MOD has sites in many parts of the country, and internationally, and staff need to travel between them. For example, travel enables Ministers and senior leaders to visit troops on operations or to hold discussions with other governments aimed at reducing conflict.</p><br /><p>We have achieved savings of over £60 million a year in non-operational travel since 2009-10 and plan to make further savings of 10% over the rest of this Parliament. These savings will be delivered in a number of ways, including a reduction in travel where the business need can be met by alternative arrangements such as video or audio conferencing.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-12-04T14:19:02.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432669/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432669/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-26","Ministry of Defence: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his departmental expenditure was on travel for (a) military staff, (b) civilian staff and (c) Ministers in each of the previous five years.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","17779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432670","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-03","<p>The two Strike Brigades will provide a rapidly deployable agile force, with enhanced range, speed, protection and firepower, significantly enhancing the UK's ability to respond to international crises.</p><p>As previously announced on 3 September 2014 by My right hon. Friend the Defence Secretary (Michael Fallon) (Official Report, column 19WS) a contract has been awarded to deliver 589 Ajax vehicles. Detailed allocation plans have yet to be finalised. Fielding of Strike Brigades will start from 2018, delivering an initial operating capability in 2021 and moving towards Full Operating Capability from 2025.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","17930","2015-12-03T16:35:12.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432670/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432670/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-26","Rapid Reaction Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what timetable he has set for the introduction of the Rapid Strike brigade as set out in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","17790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432671","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-01","<p>I apologise for the time taken to respond to the hon. Member's letters. I will write to the hon. Member shortly on this issue.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-01T16:32:32.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432671/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432671/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-26","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to answer the letters from the hon. Member for Tewkesbury dated 20 July and 21 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","17802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432672","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-03","<p>The Boeing P-8A Poseidon Maritime Patrol Aircraft entered service with the United States Navy in November 2013. Under current plans, we anticipate that it will enter service with the RAF in the UK during financial year 2019-20. Exact dates for entering service and for all nine aircraft to be operational are yet to be agreed.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-12-03T16:17:00.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432672/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/432672/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-26","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the first Boeing P8 Maritime Patrol Aircraft came into full service; and by what date he plans for all nine to be operational.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","17832"
